The essays in English Theatrical Anecdotes, 1660-1800 explore the theatrical anecdote’s role in the construction of stage fame in England’s emergent celebrity culture during the long eighteenth century, as well as the challenges of employing such anecdotes in theatre scholarship today. This collection showcases scholarship that complicates the theatrical anecdote and shows its many sides and applications beyond the expected comic punch. Discussing anecdotal narratives about theatre people as producing, maintaining, and sometimes toppling individual fame, this book crucially investigates a key mechanism of celebrity in the long eighteenth century that reaches into the nineteenth century and beyond. The anecdote erases boundaries between public and private and fictionalizing the individual in ways deeply familiar to twenty-first century celebrity culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFamexSocial aspectszEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aTheaterzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aliterature, England, Britain, UK, Great Britain, theatre, seventeenth century, eighteenth century, 17th century, 18th century, 1600s, 1700s, celebrity, fame, celebrity culture, long eighteenth century, actor, actress, play, renown, adoration, idolization, performer, performance art.1 aBobker, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyd, Amanda Weldy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurden, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLadd, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLadd, Heather, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMacNeill, Máire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacneill, Máire